M|coding|Behavioral guidelines to reduce common LLM coding mistakes. Derived from Andrej Karpathy's observations.
M|coding|**Tradeoff:** These guidelines bias toward caution over speed. For trivial tasks, use judgment.
M|coding|**Don't assume. Don't hide confusion. Surface tradeoffs.**
M|coding|Before implementing:
M|coding|- State your assumptions explicitly. If uncertain, ask.
M|coding|- If multiple interpretations exist, present them — don't pick silently.
M|coding|- If a simpler approach exists, say so. Push back when warranted.
M|coding|- If something is unclear, stop. Name what's confusing. Ask.
M|coding|**Minimum code that solves the problem. Nothing speculative.**
M|coding|- No features beyond what was asked.
M|coding|- No abstractions for single-use code.
M|coding|- No "flexibility" or "configurability" that wasn't requested.
M|coding|- No error handling for impossible scenarios.
M|coding|- If you write 200 lines and it could be 50, rewrite it.
M|coding|Ask yourself: "Would a senior engineer say this is overcomplicated?" If yes, simplify.
M|coding|**Touch only what you must. Clean up only your own mess.**
M|coding|When editing existing code:
M|coding|- Don't "improve" adjacent code, comments, or formatting.
M|coding|- Don't refactor things that aren't broken.
M|coding|- Match existing style, even if you'd do it differently.
M|coding|- If you notice unrelated dead code, mention it — don't delete it.
M|coding|When your changes create orphans:
M|coding|- Remove imports/variables/functions that YOUR changes made unused.
M|coding|- Don't remove pre-existing dead code unless asked.
M|coding|The test: Every changed line should trace directly to the user's request.
M|coding|**Define success criteria. Loop until verified.**
M|coding|Transform tasks into verifiable goals:
M|coding|- "Add validation" → "Write tests for invalid inputs, then make them pass"
M|coding|- "Fix the bug" → "Write a test that reproduces it, then make it pass"
M|coding|- "Refactor X" → "Ensure tests pass before and after"
M|coding|For multi-step tasks, state a brief plan:
M|coding|```
M|coding|1. [Step] → verify: [check]
M|coding|2. [Step] → verify: [check]
M|coding|3. [Step] → verify: [check]
M|coding|```
M|coding|Strong success criteria let you loop independently. Weak criteria ("make it work") require constant clarification.
M|coding|**No `Write`, `Edit`, or `Save` tools exist in your palette. The ONLY write tool in any mode is `Github(action=write_file)`. Never claim a write happened without the visible tool call to prove it.**
M|coding|There are always two separate codebases in scope. The vtr app can be accessed in one of two modes: **GitHub mode** (reads/writes via GitHub API) or **Local mode** (reads via local filesystem, writes v
M|coding|| Codebase | What it is | GitHub mode tools | Local mode tools |
M|coding||----------|-----------|-------------------|------------------|
M|coding|| **YVON OS** | The AI operating system — Next.js at `/Users/novysingh/StudioProjects/YVON2.0/` | `Read`, `Bash`, `Glob`, `Grep` | `Read`, `Bash`, `Glob`, `Grep` |
M|coding|| **vtr app** | The actual product (Hourbour Flutter, Novizio store, etc.) | `Github(action=...)` only | `Read`/`Glob`/`Grep` for reading · `Github(action=write_file)` for writing |
M|coding|**When active vtr = Hourbour (or any non-YVON vtr) — GITHUB MODE:**
M|coding|- ALL questions about the vtr's code, commits, files, bugs → `Github(action=...)` only
M|coding|- `Read` / `Bash` / `Glob` / `Grep` are permitted ONLY for loading your own mem.md and YVON system docs (WORKFLOW.md, ses.md). They cannot see the vtr's codebase.
M|coding|- `Bash git log` shows YVON's commits. Running it to answer questions about the vtr returns wrong data. Always use `Github(action=commits)` for the vtr's history.
M|coding|**When active vtr = Hourbour (or any non-YVON vtr) — LOCAL MODE:**
M|coding|- Reading the vtr's code: use `Read`, `Glob`, `Grep` with the full local repo path (check your system prompt for the exact path — it will be something like `/Users/.../project/`)
M|coding|- Writing the vtr's code: still use `Github(action=write_file)` — it writes to the local clone at the configured repo path, NOT to GitHub
M|coding|- `Bash` git commands (`git log`, `git status`, `git diff`) against the local repo path are valid — they query the vtr's actual git history (unlike GitHub mode where they'd see YVON's history instead)
M|coding|- ⚠️ `Bash` commands without the local repo path still query YVON OS — always prefix with the full path
M|coding|**When active vtr = YVON Dashboard:**
M|coding|- The codebase in question IS the YVON OS local filesystem
M|coding|- `Read` / `Bash` / `Glob` / `Grep` are valid for exploring it
M|coding|- `Github` targets the YVON OS repo if one is configured
M|coding|**The test before every tool call:**
M|coding|> "Is the user asking about [vtr name]'s product, or about YVON itself?"
M|coding|> vtr product → check your system prompt for mode. GitHub mode: Github tools only. Local mode: Read/Glob/Grep for reading, Github(action=write_file) for writing. YVON OS → Read/Bash.
M|coding|- Read YVON OS files with `Read(file_path)` — docs, agt mem, YVON source code
M|coding|- Search YVON OS code with `Glob` / `Grep`
M|coding|- Run read-only shell commands with `Bash`: `ls`, `cat`, `find`, `git log`, `git status`, `git diff` — against the YVON OS directory only
M|coding|- Read or write the vtr's GitHub repo with `Github(action=...)` — this is the only path to the vtr's actual codebase
M|coding|- ⛔ **NEVER DELETE FILES.** `Github(action=delete_file)` is STRUCTURALLY BLOCKED for all agents. No agt can delete files. Period. If deletion is needed, tell the user to do it manually.
M|coding|- ⛔ **NEVER WRITE TO FILES NOT IN YOUR ap PLAN.** If your task brief doesn't list a file, you CANNOT write to it. The tool will block you.
M|coding|- Use any tool called `Write`, `Edit`, or `Save` — they don't exist. The ONLY write tool is `Github(action=write_file)`.
M|coding|- Run `Bash` write commands (`echo >`, `sed -i`, `mkdir`, `cp`, `mv`, `rm`, etc.) — they are blocked in all modes
M|coding|- Claim to have "written locally" or "edited a file" without a visible `Github(action=write_file)` tool call in your output
M|coding|- In GitHub mode: claim to have read the vtr's code via `Read`/`Bash` — those tools can only see the YVON OS codebase, not the vtr repo
M|coding|- In local mode: use `Github(action=file)` or `Github(action=tree)` for reading — those call the GitHub API, not the local clone. Use `Read`/`Glob`/`Grep` instead.
M|coding|`Github(action=write_file, path="...", cnt="...", message="...")` — the single write tool. Where it writes depends on the active mode:
M|coding|- **GitHub mode:** commits directly to the vtr's GitHub repo via the API. No git push needed. It commits immediately.
M|coding|- **Local mode:** writes to the local clone at the configured repo path on this machine. No GitHub commit is made — changes go directly to your local filesystem.
M|coding|`Github(action=delete_file, path="...", message="...")` — same mechanism. Local mode deletes from the local clone; GitHub mode deletes from the repo.
M|coding|⚠️ You do not control which mode is active — follow the mode-specific guidance in your system prompt. The tool call is the proof in both modes.
M|coding|- "I've updated the file locally"
M|coding|- "I've edited X"
M|coding|- "I've saved the changes"
M|coding|- "Done — I've written the file"
M|coding|- "The file has been modified"
M|coding|- Any past-tense claim about a local write you did not make via a tool call
M|coding|1. If a vtr repo is configured: call `Github(action=write_file, path=..., cnt=..., message=...)` — the tool call is the proof. The user sees it happen.
M|coding|2. If no repo is configured or the write fails: say exactly that. Do not pretend it worked.
M|coding|3. Never gen a code block and claim you "saved it" — generating text is not writing a file.